How to finance the green transition
New York — This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global battle against climate change and submit new emission reduction commitments.
The climate crisis is a matter of great importance, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We are unable to shift into high gear promptly.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private stakeholders.
 Fortunately, with the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to curb climate change is increasing.
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the United Nations Climate Action Special Envoy, CFLI was established with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," outlining how to expand green finance to support a orderly transition to a low-carbon economy, and identifying public-private collaboration opportunities to achieve the goals of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to the call from European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are prepared to show greater ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and commit to investing at least 1 trillion euros in low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed toward climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition toward a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and the most critical issue among them is climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our determination.
This summer, European countries experienced record-breaking heat and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars each year and threaten the lives of more people.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as financing new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that affects major cities around the world.
Changing investment patterns will help accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of the coal-fired power plants in the United States retired, while its clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to fewer than 100,000 in the coal industry.
In addition, an increasing number of U.S. cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies, aimed at supporting the full decarbonization of the U.S. economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investment toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive the transformational changes needed for the green transition.
These investments will yield substantial returns, including reducing the significant costs to public health caused by air pollution.
In addition, we can take numerous measures to guide the necessary funding.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks and did not understand the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from the impacts of extreme weather.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in more sustainable ways and enabling investors to reward those companies that take climate change seriously.
Second, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world are able to obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other projects that reduce emissions has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must increase their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax benefits have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar initiatives to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, speeding up the overcoming of intermittency issues.
In addition, better grid connectivity can allow regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply regions facing shortages.
Governments can play a leadership role in both areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to the $100 trillion global bond market, this is merely a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop sustainable finance classification standards, so that investors can compare similar projects, just like standard bonds.
Better and more information on carbon footprints can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment into low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
